##IAM & AWS CLI

#IAM = Identity and Access Management, Global service
IAM : Users and Groups
Users or Groups can be assigned JSON documents called policies
The least privilege principle 

#IAM Policies
How to add user?
Add permissions / add inline policy
IAM- Password Policy

#*Multi Factor Authentication – MFA
MFA = password you know + security device you own

#*MFA devices options in AWS
a. Virtual MFA device : Google Authenticator / Authy
b. Universal 2nd factor(U2F) Security Key
c. Hardware Key Fob MFA Device
d. Hardware Key Fob MFA Device for AWS GovCloud (US)

#How to access AWS?
a.	AWS Management Console
b.	AWS Command Line Interface (CLI)
c.	AWS Software Developer Kit (SDK)

#IAM Security Tools:
a.	IAM Credentials Report
b.	IAM Access Advisor

#IAM Guidelines & Best Practices:
a.	Don’t  use the root account except for AWS account setup
b.	One physical user = One AWS user
c.	Assign users to groups and assign permissions to group
d.	Create a strong password policy
e.	Create and use Roles for giving permissions to AWS services
f.	Use Access Keys for Programmatic Access ( CLI / SDK)
g.	Audit permission of your account with the IAM Credentials Report

#IAM Section – Summary:
User : mapped to a physical user, has a password for AWS Console
Groups : contains users only 
Policies: JSON document that outlines permissions for users or groups
Roles: for EC2 instances or AWS services
Security : MFA + Password Policy
Access Keys : access AWS using the CLI or SDK
Audit: IAM Credential Report & IAM Access Advisor

